UML:TaggedValue.value:
A SpatialEntity is part of a soil description. It provides a link between a notional feature (description package) and one spatial representation of it, or part of it. (Sites, Transects, Exposures, Surface Traces and Intercepts, etc) * the specific bounded occurrence, such as a map polygon * the SpatialEntity carries a geometry or shape - the association with a Soil or Landscape Feature provides the specification of all the other descriptors - the association with a Sampling Feature provides the context and dimensionality
A SpatialEntity is always associated with some sampling feature - e.g. a Soil Sample, a Landscape, a Soil Layer etc.

UML:TaggedValue.value: SpatialEntity observationMethod is a metadata snippet indicating how the spatial extent of the mapped feature was determined. ObservationMethod is a convenience property that provides a quick and dirty approach to observation metadata when data are reported using a feature view (as opposed to observation view). This property corresponds (loosely) to ISO19115 Lineage. (eg: digitised, Global Positioning System, published map, field observation, aerial photography, field survey

UML:TaggedValue.value: Quantitative values define the radius of an uncertainty buffer around a mappedFeature (eg: a positionAccuracy of 100 m for a line feature defines a buffer polygon of total width 200 m centred on the line). Corresponds to ISO19115 DQ_PositionalAccuracy.

UML:TaggedValue.value: Reciprocal of equivalent scale of resolution for delineation of a feature's geometry. This is in contrast to positionalAccuracy which is a measure of how well a feature is located relative to other features in the geographic reference system.

UML:TaggedValue.value: Points to the landscape features which describe the spatial entity.
Points to any number of spatial entities that are occurrences of the Landscape feature. Spatial entities may all be from a single map or from several maps.
An abstract parent class of those features that may be spatially located in the landscape.
Relationship to allow relating features in the landscape to each other. For example, the relationship between soils and the landscape, vegetation and the landscape or soils and vegetation.

A data type to capture upper and lower depth boundary values. Treated as a special range for depths where the "upper" value will be numerically smaller than the "lower" depth as opposed to a (e.g.) "DiscreteQuantityRange" where the upper value will be larger than the lower value. Different from the INSPIRE "RangeType" dataType also used for depth values but where the deeper boundary is referred to as the "upperBoundary" (unless -ve values are used for depth).
The 'lower' depth boundary, that is the deepest or furthermost from the surface.
The 'upper' depth boundary, that is the closest to the surface.
Placeholder for terms to describe the relationship between landscape feature components

Terms that will come from a vocabulary appropriate for the observationMethod property. (eg: digitised, Global Positioning System, published map, field observation, aerial photography, field survey)
ObservationMethod is a convenience property that provides a quick and dirty approach to observation metadata when data are reported using a feature view (as opposed to observation view).
